no longer human by osamu dazai is a semi-autobiographical novel about the authors life. dazai is known for first person autobiographical fiction (aka this shit reads like a spam post, they‚Äôre aren‚Äôt chapters but notebooks). many of the elements that happen to the main character yozo were taken from dazai‚Äôs life, and shortly after the writing of this book he committed suicide, leading many to believe that this book is his will. dazai (which is just a pen name) spent most of his life depressed or struggling with addiction, having attempted suicide four times with the last one being successful (mf has more privilege then me üòî), which is reflected in yozo. ever since yozo was born, he‚Äôs felt disqualified to be human, despising the two facedness of humanity and was sexually assaulted by his servants. these traumas would lead him to indulge himself with smoking, alcohol and prostitutes, and would continuously lament about his hatred of humanity and its nature. he plays himself as a clown in order to never reveal his true self to anyone, essentially ostracizing himself to save the pain of a relationship. yozo represents nihilism but most of all the pain of existentialism. though yozo often makes disgusting and morally wrong actions, the book concludes from an outside point of view that he was a good child. it depicts depression and the cynical cycle of hatred in the most real light, and it comes off as authentic and not as edgy or rebellious. yozo feels indescribably alienated but finds comfort in that alienation, as many rather be comfortable then be better. aight i‚Äôm done with this formal ass voice this book da shit ong. like he basically describes so many existential thoughts and questions what it means to live. he depicts mental illness as what it really is, because mental illness causes people to do a lot of shitty things (does that mean they shouldn‚Äôt be held responsible? Just finished reading the metamorphosis. crazy how kafka is able to pack so many ideas in such a short story. so ig spoiler ahead. one theme is that the idea of something is scarier then the appearance. the whole family is horrified and disgusted by how gregor looks but when he dies they‚Äôre completely fine with looking at him. which signifies that what really horrified his family was the idea that he became such a creature rather then his appearance which we are first led to believe. another theme is the arbitrariness and abursidity that money holds in our society. when gregor first wakes up from his metamorphosis the only thing that really stresses on his mind is his job and work, and not the fact that he‚Äôs an insect. this at first seems absurd to the reader but slowly after seeing how the family has had to suffer from the lost of his income, it really becomes apparent how important money is and why that stress meant so much. along with this life is just absurd, things just happen without any intention and many of the characters are not extremely surprised by his appearance. sympathy has its boundaries, even tho it‚Äôs a shit thing to say he is actually a burden to a family. it causes him to be depressed and to jill himself but at the end of the day people have to prioritize there own lives. also the notion that physical form dictates mental form is also a theme. because he is physically an insect he slowly becomes more and more like an insect mentally, even in his attempts to reject that metamorphosis. i think the biggest theme out of this whole book is regardless of appearance to treat everyone the same. like i remember my ela 10 teacher told us that when he asked homeless people what the worst part is that when people ignore them because it Jun 17, 2021, 10:05 PM
so i just listened to 11.5 hours of crime and punishment today so it‚Äôs time for a review time. first of all i‚Äôm kind of disappointed but that is because i thought very highly of the book. i thought it would be easily a 10 and contend with eva but that didn‚Äôt happen. really the title is basically the story, the protagonist does a crime and his punishment is outlined. it explores the flaws in western philosophy such as existentialism, utilitarianism, nihilism and ubermensch (even before neisctzhe) and basically concludes that the philosophical beliefs of russian christianity were better (which was quite a conflict during dostoyevsky time of writing). i think the best explored theme is that crimes or immoral actions will weigh on the human conscience and causes the criminal to be unable to receive or give love properly. one must repent or take responsibility for there actions. but along with that one must receive unconditional love (even if they are unable to accept it) in order to change or be better. it also explores how shit poverty is and how horrible it is. some aspects it was explored well and others it‚Äôs meh. i think the main problem i have which won‚Äôt let me rate it higher is that the themes are just not explored as well as i thought and the book does not represent much; it only represents one idea and not multiple ideas or even the entirety of life. i don‚Äôt feel the complexity of the issue has been explored lots. that being said the ability of dostoyevsky to deconstruct atheistic philosophy is admirable and is one of the first to shit on existentialism and utilitarianism in literature. but what i find most impressive about dostoyevsky writing is his writing. i found myself very entertained throughout the novel and very emotional at the end. he builds up the characters very well and i think this is one of the best novels (in terms of appeal) i‚Äôve ever read. there‚Äôs a reason i was able to sit for almost 12 hours reading this book. it‚Äôs fucking entertaining even with its somewhat mundane plot. and i felt my heart aching at the final couple of chapters. this book truly is able to make the reader very emotional and make one feel as guilty as the protagonist.

okay book review first. brave new world. at first i was reading this book and i was like bruh another dystopia. i hate dystopias because they state facts instead of exploring the reason behind them. ngl john killing himself actually saved the entire book. because john lives in the other extreme of civilization, while civilization only cares for happiness, john only cares for truth and completely ignores his humanity. they are the same robot in two different ways. by showing this stark contrast the book ultimately concludes that we need truth and happiness to live and by living in one extreme we lose our humanity, which is a really basic point but the way it‚Äôs executed is done really well. i think the main reason it‚Äôs done so well is that we are led to believe that john way of living is so much better, but realize that it‚Äôs worse or even much worse then the civilizations way of living. by exploring how easy it is to fall into the trap, ultimately the author shows how easy it is to live in a dystopia. ultimately the last chapters allow this book to serve as a critique on character rather then a critique on society. what a i disliked about the book (and dystopia in general) is that they create this world that‚Äôs a dystopia and it‚Äôs obvious why it could be reached and why it‚Äôs so shit. simply pointing out these facts is a really boring and unimpactful way of exploring being human. but by exploring the descent and the personal emotions that lead to flawed mindsets speaks more volume and is much more relatable. by exploring the fragility of humanity through a single character rather then a society shows the complexity of being human and the want to live in an ideal world. ultimately the end saves this book by its ass. 7/10. first day of school was alright. was Jul 31, 2020, 8:36 PM
dog shit album review. Blonde is an album that explores Frank‚Äôs past relationships and immaturity. Often, the songs are Frank reflecting upon his own life and relationships, reflecting upon his mistakes and immaturities. This allows the listener to relate, as often many of those reflections are common, especially after a romantic relationship. Basically this put me into my feels. A major theme to Blonde is duality. The entire album is filled with this idea of duality, including the title name. The official title name is Blonde but on the album cover the title name is Blond. Though they mean the same thing, blond in French is the masculine form whilst blonde is the feminine form. This minor detail relates to the album as Frank struggles with the duality of his masculinity and femininity. Another example of duality is through the guitar riff in the ninth track ‚ÄúNights.‚Äù This guitar riff occurs exactly 30 minutes in the 60 minute album, splitting Blonde ‚Äãinto two parts. By splitting the album into two parts we are able to see a change in his attitudes towards his past. In the first eight songs, Frank is reminiscing and trying to relive the memories he had towards his past lovers, even trying to win them back. The songs in the second part shows Frank accepting the past and wishing the best for his past lovers. I could go on for days about this theme but I‚Äôm just going to end it here because honestly bro this too long fam. The production on ‚ÄãBlonde‚Äã ‚Äãis honestly one of my favourite things on the album. If I‚Äôm going to be honest I never listened to the lyrics closely most of the time but rather just for the musical appeal of the album as a whole. The production is a perfect balance of experimentation and appeal, not too strange but not too common. Along with this, the vocals combine perfectly with the production and allows the listener to feel immersed in the world Frank creates. Even though the production is immaculate, for me personally it took me a couple of listens to get used to the sound. For me personally, the songs with the best production are ‚ÄúPink + White,‚Äù ‚ÄúSelf Control,‚Äù and ‚ÄúNights.‚Äù I could go on and on about this album, dissecting every lyric
